To estimate the relative size of the resummed corrections with respect to NLO, the $K$~factor

is defined and shown in figure~\ref{fig:st_k} for centre-of-mass energies of 8 and 13 TeV. The NNLL predictions are always higher than NLO, and with their ratio becoming larger as the stop mass increases. For 8 TeV, the increase is around 10\% at low stop masses and can become as large as almost 100\% at high stop masses, as expected when the production is taking place closer to the hadronic threshold, $m_{{\tilde{t}}_1} \approx \sqrt{S}/2$. The NNLL corrections are furthermore always larger than the previously known NLL corrections. The difference between the NNLO$_\mathrm{Approx}$ and NNLO$_\mathrm{Approx}$+NNLL predictions indicates the importance of the higher-order logarithms and their cross terms with the Coulomb and hard-matching coefficients, in particular at high stop masses close to threshold. For 13 TeV, the qualitative behaviour of the $K$ factors is similar to 8 TeV, albeit smaller at the same stop mass due to the hadronic threshold being further away. The small peak near $m_{{\tilde{t}}_1}\approx 1500$ GeV stems from the behaviour of the hard-matching coefficient for the $gg$ initial state, in particular due to the superposition of two effects where the virtual corrections develop a threshold for $m_{{\tilde{t}}_1} = m_{\tilde{g}}$ and $m_{{\tilde{t}}_1}=m_t+m_{\tilde{g}}$ leading to the observed behaviour close to these masses\footnote{For the hard-matching coefficient of the similar process of light-flavoured squark-antisquark production $\mathcal{C}^{(1)}_{gg\to{\tilde{q}}\bar{{\tilde{q}}},I}$ (see appendix B of \cite{Beenakker:2013mva}, p.\ 17), it has been checked that this behaviour is also arising at a similar mass, with mainly the $\log^2\left(x_{{\tilde{g}}{\tilde{g}}}(4m_{\tilde{q}}^2)\right)$ (with the argument $x_{{\tilde{g}}{\tilde{g}}}(4m_{\tilde{q}}^2) = \frac{\sqrt{1-m_{\tilde{g}}^2/m_{\tilde{q}}^2}-1}{\sqrt{1-m_{\tilde{g}}^2/m_{\tilde{q}}^2}+1}$) and the $\mathrm{Li}_2\left(\frac{m_{\tilde{q}}^2}{m_{\tilde{g}}^2}\right)$ terms stemming from the two thresholds mentioned above being responsible for it.}. The similar hard-matching coefficient of light-flavoured squark-antisquark production exhibits the same behaviour when the mass of the produced squarks is equal to the gluino mass, see \cite{Beenakker:2011sf}.

